The key may be to look at exactly what URIs the browser does request, in 
both the &#39;live web&#39; and the wayback-replay cases. (Ignore the case where 
you do hand-patching for now.)

Two options for collecting such lists are:

(1) the built-in developer tools (or &#39;Firebug&#39;) console of the browser, 
which has a &#39;net&#39;/&#39;network&#39; tab that can show all requests

(2) setting the browser to go through an intervening logging proxy

When you have lists from both situations, is there a request the 
wayback-replay visit is not making at all, or making and receiving a 
404, compared to the &#39;live web&#39;?

If so, it&#39;s possible that something uncommon about the page -- in its 
use of relative/declared-BASE URIs, or perhaps in active javascript that 
composes the CSS to request -- prevents the normal Wayback rewriting 
from working.

If the situation is characterizable, it might be a Wayback bug that can 
be fixed.

- Gordon

